<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-667-476  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 667 476.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 18 1989 v23 n38 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Razing structured approaches. (object-oriented design seen asimprovement over top-down approach) (Soft Talk ) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>O'Connell, Daniel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Object-oriented program design is an improvement over thestructured or top-down approach, especially in technical systemssuch as compilers, operating system utilities and communicationsprotocols.andP;  Top-down approach specifies that all systems be viewedin hierarchical relationships.andP;  In technical software, hierarchiesare not easily defined or may not exist.andP;  Instead, the datastructures being manipulated and moved between program componentsare the key to developing a functional system.andP;  Object-orientedprogramming causes the designer to see these components as objectsand object classes that the system manipulates.andP;  Object-orienteddesign can also handle complex techniques such as concurrency,which is important because of the computer industry's move tomassive parallelism and concurrent programming languages.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Object-Oriented ProgrammingSoftware DesignMethodsTop-Down Design.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>